comment.body: [Two](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/012013) [models](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/012015) of ASW0009lly.  This kind of configuration tends to model well.   These models are terrible, which suggests this object is not a lens.

The dependence on redshifts is not simply zsource over zlens!   We can go through the formulas another time.

Fortunately, though, redshift information can be put in after modelling.   That is, models made with the default values of redshift can be recalibrated afterwards with the correct values.   The mass maps, synthetic images etc won't change, only their calibration will.    [This is no longer true if you have two or more source redshifts -- but we probably don't have any such candidates as yet.]

*So you can ignore the redshift sliders for now, because the information can be added to models later.*

comment.body: Just join the discussion threads on objects you find interesting.   The 'My Candidates' collection logs the images you've marked that are not sims, and you can make more collections.   For example, ASW0009io9 has had some lively discussion over the last few hours and looks very promising.

boards.title: How do you know if you have found one that's not a simulation?

comment.body:
The things with spikes are foreground stars from our own galaxy.   The spikes are ghost images of the struts that hold up the telescope mirrors.

For the colours --- we are seeing a composite of several images taken through different infrared filters and rendered as red-green-blue.   Sometimes the component images aren't matched up quite right, and then as you suggested, bright sources give weird-looking results.

boards.title: What's with the blue and green?

comment.body: As @Capella05 said, [9105](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/009105) looks the most convincing so far.

Tried revising 9014 by @ElisabethB with result [9037](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/9037) which looks like a step backwards.

Interesting though, that the mass distribution in this configurations tends to align with the observed galaxy, which suggests that [9014](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/9014) and its relatives are on the right track.
How about if you rotate the configuration so that the inner saddle point is at 5 o'clock?

Anyone feel like [modelling](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/?mid=864) the lens?  The paper does have a model, but it would be interesting to see if other models agree, and @rafael_kueng has now linked the image from the paper to SpaghettiLens.

This is a certainly a hard one, since we're guessing about the position of the image, and even the arc isn't super clear.  Still, the bleeding edge is where the best research happens!

Tried [this modification](http://mite.physik.uzh.ch/data/8892) putting the counter-image more or less opposite the arc.
